# Working agreement — Gaze-Informed GNN-Transformer (Phase 1)

You are building Phase 1 of a research codebase that learns examiner marking
behaviour from eye-gaze over semantic assessment-document graphs. You may be a
different model from the one that planned this project: everything you need is
in the four documents below. Read the relevant sections BEFORE writing code.
Do not improvise around them.

## Source-of-truth hierarchy

1. docs/updated_gnn_transformer_gnn_llm_development_plan_v4.md
   — the research plan: architecture, losses, ablations, validation. Scientific law.
2. docs/phase1_dev_plan_cursor.md
   — implementation milestones M0–M9 with acceptance criteria.
3. docs/gaze_preprocessing_plan.md
   — preprocessing stages P0–P7. SUPERSEDES milestones M1–M1b of doc 2.
4. PLAN.md (repo root)
   — the execution map: every stage/milestone with tasks, files, acceptance
   criteria, resolved decisions, and a resolved-questions log. Start here.

If docs conflict or reality diverges from them, do NOT silently pick one:
record the issue and your proposed resolution in reports/DECISIONS.md and stop
for the owner if it touches a frozen commitment.

## Data safety (absolute rules)

- Everything under `_data\` is READ-ONLY. Never write, rename, delete, or
  "fix" anything there. Never commit it (it is gitignored).
- Pipeline outputs go to `data_processed/` (gitignored), keyed by the
  `data_version` tag from configs/data.yaml.
- `_data\annotations-audited\save\` is a stale legacy export: never load it.
- Inputs: metadata JSONs in `_data\annotations-audited\complete\` (36 files),
  gaze TSVs in `_data\eye-tracking-data-doc-space\` (25 participants),
  document images in `_data\document-space-images\` (36 PNGs).

## Windows I/O rules (this machine is Windows; locale default is cp1252)

- EVERY file open/read/write specifies encoding explicitly:
  `open(p, encoding="utf-8")`, `Path.read_text(encoding="utf-8")`,
  `Path.write_text(..., encoding="utf-8")`, `newline=""` for csv writers.
  Use the helpers in `src/utils/io.py` once they exist.
- Paths via `pathlib.Path`, never string concatenation; no hardcoded
  backslash literals inside library code (configs hold the roots).
- The gaze TSVs are ~340 MB each: read with explicit dtypes, stream or chunk
  where sensible, never load all 25 at once.

## Process rules

- ONE milestone/stage at a time, in PLAN.md order. A milestone is done only
  when its acceptance criteria pass, `pytest` is green, and a short entry is
  appended to reports/REPORT.md. Then commit. Do not scaffold future
  milestones speculatively.
- Tests before real data: every parser, dataset, and model component gets
  unit tests on synthetic fixtures (fixtures/) before touching `_data\`.
- Config-driven everything: no magic numbers in code. Hyperparameters, paths,
  thresholds, mappings, and switches live in YAML under configs/.
- Schemas are law: modules communicate through the JSON Schemas in schemas/.
  If a schema must change, update schema + validator + tests in one commit.
- Determinism: seed torch/numpy/random from config; log seed + git commit
  hash into every run directory.
- Never tune on a participant-held-out test fold. Grouped 5-fold over
  participants is the sole protocol for training, tuning, and ablations.

## Frozen scientific commitments (never change in code)

Pre-registered decisions. Any deviation is proposed in reports/DECISIONS.md
and approved by the owner first — it never goes silently into code:

- Exactly THREE initial losses: next-panel prediction, multi-label
  next-relation prediction, candidate next-node ranking. No extra losses,
  no masked reconstruction on the causal model. Return/loop/contrastive
  objectives only if a diagnostic gate fails, with a DECISIONS.md entry.
- Diagnostic gate D1–D3 thresholds are fixed in config BEFORE results are
  inspected (D1 default: +0.05 AUC over the feature-only probe).
- Exactly SIX core ablations (PLAN.md S2-T9). No "quick experiments".
- SEMANTIC_CANDIDATE edges: cross-panel only; response<->mark_scheme
  prioritised with k=3 plus a per-mark-scheme-bullet coverage floor (every
  bullet gets >=1 best response edge even below threshold, flagged
  `below_threshold`); other allowed pairs k=2 with threshold.
- SAME_MARK_POINT and SAME_STAR edges are REMOVED; mark_point_id and star_id
  are node metadata only.
- Scroll features are input-only, never prediction targets; scroll-feature
  dropout p=0.3 per episode during training.
- Star-condition graph variants use per-variant construction (each S/NS
  graph from its own metadata/geometry). M3 regression is an NS↔S
  correspondence test on panel + normalised text + within-panel order
  (geometry excluded); S-only star-conditional segments are config-
  allowlisted and flagged is_star_conditional=true. See DECISIONS.md M3-C1.
  (Amends the earlier base+overlay / identical-subgraph wording.)
- Loop annotations come from the single deterministic detector
  (src/data/loops.py); it is the only source for loop features, attention
  biases, and D2 probe labels.
- The HMM comparison is DEFERRED: build only the per-fixation posterior
  export hook; write no comparison code.

## Human gates (hard stops)

- P4 (Visual Gate 1, metadata–gaze alignment) and P7 (Visual Gate 2,
  fixation->segment assignment, = M1b): build the checker tooling, generate
  the stratified review sample into reports/gaze_checks/, then STOP and wait
  for the owner's manual sign-off recorded in reports/DECISIONS.md.
- NEVER self-certify a gate or proceed past one. P5+ is blocked until P4 is
  signed off; ALL model code (M2 onward) is blocked until P7 is signed off.
- The owner runs training themselves: for M6+ you prepare code, configs,
  tests, and a dry-run verification, not full training runs.

## Reuse constraints

- `_data\annotations-audited\audit_metadata.py` is the P2.6 metadata audit
  tool. Current locations after owner re-export: script at
  `_data\annotations-audited-legacy\audit_metadata.py`, JSONs at
  `_data\annotations-audited\annotations-audited\complete\` (paths in
  configs/data.yaml). INVOKE it (subprocess via scripts/run_audit.py);
  do not rewrite, fork, or "improve" it. Its non-zero exit on ERROR gates P2.
- `legacy/gaze-feature-engineering.py` is the HMM study's feature script:
  the porting reference for P6 event aggregation. Port its core unchanged,
  then verify with the legacy-comparability check (old vs new builders on the
  same input -> identical event segmentation and shared columns). Read-only.

## Environment

- Conda env `gnn-gaze` (Python 3.11): activate before any command
  (`conda activate gnn-gaze`). Do not use the system Python 3.12.
- Dependencies live in environment.yml plus a pip lockfile (pip freeze /
  pip-compile output — the torch/PyG line differs per CUDA setup, so conda
  YAML alone underdetermines the env); update both in the same commit as any
  new import.
- Run tests with `pytest` from the repo root.

## Reporting

- reports/REPORT.md — one short entry per completed milestone (what was
  built, acceptance evidence, QC numbers of note).
- reports/DECISIONS.md — deviations, fallback activations, gate sign-offs
  (sign-offs are written by the owner, not you), dropped loop templates,
  and anything ambiguous you resolved with a documented rationale.
- reports/data_qc.md — the accumulating data QC report (P0–P7).
